WEBVTT

00:00:35.920 --> 00:00:43.280
Hello everyone. Welcome once again to WordPress 
Accessibility Day 2020. This is a 24 hour long

00:00:43.280 --> 00:00:50.240
event where we talk about accessibility. My name is 
Ahmed Kabir Chaion and I'm working as a Business

00:00:50.240 --> 00:00:55.040
Development Manager at weDevs. I'm also a regular 
contributor to the making WordPress documentation,

00:00:55.040 --> 00:01:01.760
design, polyglots, accessibility, hosting, community, 
learn WordPress, and Marketing group. I will be your host

00:01:01.760 --> 00:01:09.280
for this session. You're here for the 10 am UTC
talk with Calum Ryan. Please feel free to add your

00:01:09.280 --> 00:01:16.720
question to the YouTube chat kit and we'll answer 
those at the end. So how do we approach accessibility

00:01:16.720 --> 00:01:21.440
while testing in a way that's sufficiently 
comprehensive from a technical perspective,

00:01:22.480 --> 00:01:28.400
at the same time presentable to clients 
without being technically knowledge and

00:01:28.400 --> 00:01:34.720
who may themselves have a disability. So that's 
a question posed specifically for this talk.

00:01:34.720 --> 00:01:40.800
So in this talk the speaker will explain some of 
the approaches and attention to detail it takes

00:01:40.800 --> 00:01:45.280
to test and present accessibility 
issues in websites that's accessible.

00:01:45.920 --> 00:01:51.200
The points that are will be covered using 
WordPress to help make accessible, accessibility

00:01:51.200 --> 00:01:56.800
reports for clients, the conversations with clients 
as part of the accessibility testing process

00:01:56.800 --> 00:02:03.280
before and after, and what the benefits are 
of using this approach. Our speaker Calum

00:02:03.280 --> 00:02:10.080
is an Accessibility Consultant for dxw, helping the 
public sector make their websites more accessible.

00:02:10.080 --> 00:02:15.680
His background is in front and web 
development and user interface design,

00:02:15.680 --> 00:02:21.840
having worked in the web industry for around 10 
years, which brings to this session accessible, um

00:02:24.960 --> 00:02:28.320
which brings to this session making accessibility,

00:02:29.040 --> 00:02:35.840
making accessible accessibility reports.
Apologies for that Calum, take it away.

00:02:38.160 --> 00:02:44.800
[Calum] Thank you. So I was really in pleased to 
give this talk about creating accessibility

00:02:44.800 --> 00:02:51.600
reports, which are accessible. And 
I, I work for a company called dxw

00:02:52.240 --> 00:02:59.360
who are based in the UK in London 
and Leeds has around 70 people roughly.

00:03:00.240 --> 00:03:04.640
And we design, build, operate 
through digital public services.

00:03:09.840 --> 00:03:20.000
And within dxw I'm, I work in GovPress which 
specifically works with WordPress. We have lots

00:03:20.000 --> 00:03:27.040
of clients who use WordPress. They're all public 
sector mainly. And throughout the past few months

00:03:27.040 --> 00:03:33.760
I've been working on making the websites 
more accessible and this is for the latest

00:03:35.040 --> 00:03:41.840
legislation which is now a legal requirement 
in the UK for all public sector websites to

00:03:41.840 --> 00:03:47.840
be accessible. If you take a look 
at accessibility.campaign.gov.uk

00:03:48.640 --> 00:03:54.880
there's more explanation on what that involves,
the regulations and who that applies to.

00:03:56.480 --> 00:04:05.280
So within organization of GovPress, I'm 
the only accessibility expert and it's been

00:04:05.280 --> 00:04:14.640
my responsibility to interpret a lot of that 
information from the WCAG guidelines, the latest

00:04:14.640 --> 00:04:24.560
guidelines which all public sector organizations 
must comply to. So if some of you, I mean it depends,

00:04:25.280 --> 00:04:31.520
um I'm sure there's a whole range of people 
listening to this talk um, but if you're more

00:04:31.520 --> 00:04:36.960
technically minded you might have already 
seen these guidelines. They are an extensive

00:04:37.600 --> 00:04:43.200
documentation and listing of all the different 
requirements for having an accessible website.

00:04:43.920 --> 00:04:50.720
I've probably spent some, quite a 
few hours bedtime reading for this. It's

00:04:50.720 --> 00:04:54.880
uh, it's not the sort of thing you can just 
read off in an hour. It's certainly something

00:04:54.880 --> 00:04:59.680
you need to get your head around when you're 
looking at how accessible websites should be.

00:05:01.760 --> 00:05:06.400
In those guidelines I can summarize 
that websites need to be perceivable,

00:05:07.040 --> 00:05:09.840
operable, understandable and robust.

00:05:12.160 --> 00:05:16.269
So that's a lot of criteria to present to 
clients and what I'm looking at, in terms of

00:05:20.560 --> 00:05:27.840
report, is um for clients to understand the 
importance of having accessible websites

00:05:29.120 --> 00:05:35.520
and for that reports being useful to them, 
that not only before, but after the report,

00:05:35.520 --> 00:05:41.040
they can see which fixes have been done 
and which fixes are the most critical,

00:05:41.040 --> 00:05:46.320
need to be done and which are less important,
but still need to be looked at at some point.

00:05:49.680 --> 00:05:53.200
In terms of the report going 
forward as well, it's a useful

00:05:54.000 --> 00:06:00.480
tool for the clients that we have to create their 
own accessibility statement which is a requirement

00:06:01.520 --> 00:06:06.800
for this guidelines at the moment. For 
certainly in the UK for the legislation

00:06:06.800 --> 00:06:11.200
that even if your website is fully accessible 
you still have an accessibility statement.

00:06:15.120 --> 00:06:23.680
So in terms of actually creating an accessibility 
report there's a methodology which you can look at

00:06:23.680 --> 00:06:33.280
from w3.org which gives a good in-depth listing of 
all the different criteria to look through and how

00:06:33.280 --> 00:06:41.040
to actually structure your accessibility report.
Now this is alone something we wouldn't present

00:06:41.040 --> 00:06:51.840
to our clients because it is a very, uh detailed and 
quite technical presentation on highlighting

00:06:52.400 --> 00:06:59.040
what has been tested and who has tested it and 
the types of tests that have been formed. So the

00:06:59.040 --> 00:07:07.760
challenge that I wanted to get around was looking 
at what accessibility reports do at the moment

00:07:08.640 --> 00:07:13.520
and how we can make that more accessible to not 
only the people who are going to be fixing the

00:07:13.520 --> 00:07:20.720
technical issues in the website, but the content 
issues, the overall readability of the content.

00:07:21.840 --> 00:07:28.560
So typically we'll have a lot of different people 
looking at the report so it's important that we

00:07:29.760 --> 00:07:35.440
make that report as accessible as possible to 
everybody who is not only reading it, but actually

00:07:35.440 --> 00:07:43.200
putting in information and issues into that report.
Typically there'll be many issues which are the

00:07:43.200 --> 00:07:49.200
same over different pages on websites and the 
similar solutions as well to fix those issues.

00:07:51.840 --> 00:07:59.920
And also in terms of our own example where we 
have many different clients, we need to have

00:07:59.920 --> 00:08:07.520
multiple people editing those reports or reviewing 
those reports. So we needed a solution to allow

00:08:07.520 --> 00:08:15.680
different people to look at those reports at the 
same time. We also had quite a short deadline to

00:08:16.800 --> 00:08:22.640
create all of these reports for different clients 
so having a facility to make those reports in the

00:08:22.640 --> 00:08:31.120
most efficient and accurate way was very important 
and having a way to present very technical

00:08:31.120 --> 00:08:37.920
language in a way which doesn't completely 
take over the report and make it difficult

00:08:37.920 --> 00:08:44.080
for somebody who isn't technically minded to 
get to the most important points in the report.

00:08:46.320 --> 00:08:54.720
And also a lot of our clients are just used to 
having a pdf to print off whenever they look at

00:08:54.720 --> 00:09:00.640
documents. So, although pdfs aren't inherently 
that accessible, we still have that option

00:09:00.640 --> 00:09:07.840
for the report to be printed off as 
a pdf or just as a paper printout.

00:09:10.400 --> 00:09:16.880
So creating accessibility reports, we decided to 
use WordPress because WordPress is what we use

00:09:16.880 --> 00:09:25.440
day-to-day in our company. We have a whole team 
of people who can not only work on the backend,

00:09:25.440 --> 00:09:32.320
but develop a front-end user interface, can 
customize themes and WordPress just generally

00:09:32.320 --> 00:09:39.600
has got a great community of people to make the 
whole content management system a lot more robust.

00:09:40.240 --> 00:09:47.520
Um it's important to say we don't actually use 
Gutenberg in our reports. We still use the Classic

00:09:48.160 --> 00:09:54.720
interface and that goes back to my, my 
intention is to make this report not only

00:09:55.520 --> 00:10:02.160
accessible for the front end, but accessible for 
people who are creating reports, so the whole

00:10:03.360 --> 00:10:08.480
way of entering information into 
reports is using the standard WordPress

00:10:09.600 --> 00:10:13.600
content management system, without 
any of the Gutenberg changes.

00:10:17.600 --> 00:10:26.080
So starting with how we create the reports, we 
use, um if anybody is familiar with WordPress,

00:10:26.080 --> 00:10:31.760
on the backend we use a number of existing 
plugins, where we use the Classic Editor

00:10:32.480 --> 00:10:38.720
and the override, so we don't get the 
Gutenberg presentation. We use Custom Fields,

00:10:39.520 --> 00:10:47.200
Advanced Custom Fields which gives us a few 
more options in terms of adding extra fields

00:10:47.200 --> 00:10:55.360
to content and making that more easy to add  
repeated content. So if you've got like a repeated

00:10:56.000 --> 00:11:02.800
issue or repeated criteria, we can just start 
typing the words for that criteria and it will

00:11:02.800 --> 00:11:07.840
populate field without us having to go through and 
repeat the same thing for every single web book.

00:11:10.720 --> 00:11:17.920
We, we use Custom Post Types to 
store the solutions and the criteria

00:11:18.640 --> 00:11:26.160
as a centralized area of content so we can 
refer back to those pieces of content and put

00:11:26.160 --> 00:11:31.600
those into each report, and that helps make the 
whole process a lot more efficient and accurate.

00:11:33.360 --> 00:11:40.800
And in terms of presenting the reports to 
clients we use the standard password protection

00:11:40.800 --> 00:11:47.440
on posts when we publish them, so that only their 
client with a password can review that report.

00:11:51.760 --> 00:12:01.200
In terms of actually viewing the reports, 
as a user we try and comply to WCAG 2.1 (AA)

00:12:01.200 --> 00:12:07.280
standard and so everything 
we do is client compliant to that level.

00:12:07.840 --> 00:12:14.000
You can navigate the entire report using 
keyboard, screen reader, and each of the

00:12:15.440 --> 00:12:22.400
sections are all accessible through a single 
navigation. And [unintelligible] say that the whole

00:12:22.400 --> 00:12:30.080
report is a single page. So if you want to print 
it off you can, just print off as a pdf if you wish.

00:12:31.200 --> 00:12:39.440
And in terms of beyond the technical standards, 
we also look at how readable language is so if

00:12:39.440 --> 00:12:48.880
we've got a technical term such as ARIA,
a-r-i-a, we explain what that abbreviation means

00:12:50.400 --> 00:12:58.080
and in terms of the whole sort of general 
design system, we try to apply standards which

00:12:58.080 --> 00:13:06.080
are accessible. So we have gov.uk has their own 
design system and we take influence from that so,

00:13:07.200 --> 00:13:11.600
things such as the issues which 
I'll show you in a short while

00:13:12.160 --> 00:13:19.840
uh in reports are all using standard 
components, which are accessibility tested.

00:13:22.960 --> 00:13:25.200
So let's look inside the accessibility report.

00:13:28.320 --> 00:13:34.560
Initially the report was a prototype which 
I developed without WordPress. So this

00:13:35.360 --> 00:13:44.880
report is flexible, we can use what um,
anybody could use the report in whatever CMS or

00:13:44.880 --> 00:13:51.920
even just a static template if they 
wanted to. The the current set we have is

00:13:52.800 --> 00:14:01.840
a WordPress setup that is fairly 
customizable to however you need it to be.

00:14:02.640 --> 00:14:08.880
So we start off with saying who created the report,
outlining the person that was optional if they

00:14:08.880 --> 00:14:15.760
want to have their avatar or any other information 
about when the report was done, what their role

00:14:15.760 --> 00:14:22.160
is in the organization and outlining if there 
was anybody else who quality checked the report

00:14:23.600 --> 00:14:30.880
and the overall compliance of report. So 
in some cases we have clients who stipulate

00:14:30.880 --> 00:14:36.480
they want their website to be up to AAA
standard, so we'll make a differentiation

00:14:37.040 --> 00:14:43.840
between websites which have 
been checked to AA or AAA.

00:14:48.000 --> 00:14:57.200
So in terms of outlining what we tested, we created 
a list of say how many pages or pdfs have been

00:14:57.200 --> 00:15:05.920
tested and they're now writing how it's being 
tested, so we always um specify the automated and

00:15:05.920 --> 00:15:12.000
manual tests which we've done. We have different 
browsers and [unintelligible] devices we use in the

00:15:12.000 --> 00:15:19.600
different combinations we use. Typically that will 
involve a few screen readers. We have a limited team

00:15:19.600 --> 00:15:26.960
and you can actually do that so although we have,
there are several different screen readers, we only

00:15:26.960 --> 00:15:37.120
test with what we have available at the moment.
We test with VoiceOver, NVDA and the mobile

00:15:37.120 --> 00:15:45.440
equivalent. So we've got VoiceOver on iOS and 
TalkBack on Android and Narrator on Windows.

00:15:47.280 --> 00:15:52.240
And we'll probably look at having some more 
when we maybe expand actually a bit more in

00:15:52.240 --> 00:15:57.920
the accessibility side of things. So this is 
giving an outline of just how it's being tested

00:15:58.720 --> 00:16:07.840
and that is before any of the issues 
or outlining how we fix those issues.

00:16:08.480 --> 00:16:16.320
Now the issues identified in report, we we 
typically have four user impact levels. So that

00:16:16.320 --> 00:16:28.400
starts with minor, moderates, serious and critical.
These are user impact levels we take from the axe

00:16:30.240 --> 00:16:37.760
tool by Deque and we use that as platform automated 
tests to get an overview of what are the the

00:16:37.760 --> 00:16:43.520
main issues with websites before moving on to 
the manual tests. And so within our report we

00:16:44.160 --> 00:16:53.280
we can use things such as the accordions from 
the gov uk design system to make the whole um

00:16:54.640 --> 00:17:02.240
collection of issues more simplified and 
more collated. So if there's an issue it's

00:17:02.240 --> 00:17:07.040
the same issue on different pages it's a 
lot easier to just go to that single issue

00:17:07.680 --> 00:17:14.080
and outline it within a certain section. So 
for each user impact level we have these

00:17:15.920 --> 00:17:24.240
accordion items which as a description of the 
image that we have to the right of the slide is

00:17:25.360 --> 00:17:33.040
the critical issues title, with the issue, the type 
of test, so in this case it's an automated test

00:17:34.720 --> 00:17:41.440
and where the issue is located. So in this case 
we have the home page navigation and then after

00:17:41.440 --> 00:17:49.040
that we say the level that it's been assessed 
to. So in this case the level has been WCAG 2.0, AA

00:17:49.600 --> 00:18:00.720
and the specific criteria that the issue 
is not complying with, is 1.4.3 contrast minimum.

00:18:02.400 --> 00:18:08.240
So following those details we outline 
what is the problem and who it affects.

00:18:09.200 --> 00:18:16.000
So in this case we have multiple instances of 
contrast between foreground and background colours.

00:18:16.000 --> 00:18:21.680
It doesn't meet the contrast ratio threshold 
and this includes [unintelligible] post states

00:18:22.560 --> 00:18:26.480
this has a serious user impact 
because there are many types of vision

00:18:26.480 --> 00:18:30.800
impairments where poor colour contrast could 
affect their ability to view the website.

00:18:34.240 --> 00:18:41.840
Then after that we have screenshots of 
where that is present. Now this also helps

00:18:41.840 --> 00:18:47.760
for again people who aren't technically minded 
to actually get an idea of where the problem is.

00:18:49.200 --> 00:18:54.880
So in this case we have four small screenshots 
which can be opened in a light box kind of

00:18:54.880 --> 00:19:02.720
presentation, if you want to expand it, and 
within that we may also have code samples.

00:19:03.600 --> 00:19:06.480
In this example we don't have 
that, but in some we, we would do.

00:19:09.440 --> 00:19:12.560
And finally in the issue 
is the recommended solution.

00:19:14.080 --> 00:19:20.400
We decided to put the solutions in a separate 
section. So in this case we have a small summary

00:19:20.400 --> 00:19:25.600
of what the solution is and an anchor link 
to the link to the solution further down.

00:19:31.680 --> 00:19:38.960
So the solutions section is again a collated list 
of what the solutions are. Typically a solution may

00:19:38.960 --> 00:19:46.560
be applicable to different issues and in this 
case we have an image again on the right slide

00:19:46.560 --> 00:19:54.400
with a few issues of being given solutions.
And in this case we have one about ARIA,

00:19:54.960 --> 00:20:01.520
removing ARIA, uh one about changing HTML  
here because bottom element isn't used,

00:20:03.040 --> 00:20:09.520
and another one for changing the colour contrast 
because background colour. So within each of these

00:20:09.520 --> 00:20:17.680
solutions we give the outline of the solution, how 
to fix it, in some cases the solution is aimed at

00:20:17.680 --> 00:20:24.160
a technical person. In some cases the solution is 
aimed as a content person. So in this example,

00:20:24.160 --> 00:20:29.520
we don't actually specify that, but in a future 
iteration of this whole platform we're going to

00:20:30.400 --> 00:20:37.840
make a lot clearer on who that issue, who that 
solution is aimed at in terms of responsibility.

00:20:40.240 --> 00:20:47.120
And finally we refer again to the criteria 
that the solution is applicable to and again

00:20:47.120 --> 00:20:51.680
that is another anchor link to a 
section further down in the report.

00:20:57.040 --> 00:21:03.680
And finally in the report we have the references 
section, Uh this again links you to the

00:21:04.240 --> 00:21:12.160
WCAG reference for the criteria. In each 
case we also have a secondary link to

00:21:13.280 --> 00:21:23.440
an explanation of how to understand that criteria,
a bit more in both cases the explanation is a lot

00:21:23.440 --> 00:21:30.400
more than we can write and report. And one of the 
reasons why I decided not to include an entire

00:21:30.400 --> 00:21:36.640
description of the criteria in the report itself, 
again it's just not to make it so overwhelming for

00:21:36.640 --> 00:21:43.840
different people in the report and to make the 
report a reasonable level for everybody using it.

00:21:48.640 --> 00:21:51.760
So what have we learnt from creating this platform?

00:21:53.360 --> 00:21:58.320
Certainly early on we've found there's a lot 
of information to include in a report and

00:21:58.320 --> 00:22:03.280
using visual space effectively is certainly 
something which you need to do when you've

00:22:03.280 --> 00:22:09.840
got so much information to interpret to a vast 
range of different people you might be viewing the report.

00:22:09.840 --> 00:22:19.040
We often have different clients and this is an 
example, we have the office for national statistics

00:22:19.840 --> 00:22:27.440
and in such an example as that, we may be creating 
reports to a more customized level than maybe

00:22:27.440 --> 00:22:34.160
some others in terms of the people viewing 
it, in terms of what they need from the reports.

00:22:34.160 --> 00:22:39.840
There are ways that we might consider making 
it more customizable than it is at the moment.

00:22:42.320 --> 00:22:48.720
In terms of again going, going back to who the 
issues are applicable to, who's responsible

00:22:48.720 --> 00:22:54.320
for fixing those issues, we should maybe 
look at making that bit more clearer um.

00:22:55.680 --> 00:23:02.480
In the discussions we've had with clients I've 
found that often many will feel that the report

00:23:02.480 --> 00:23:09.440
is really just for a technical person to look 
at and really they're just there just to um

00:23:09.440 --> 00:23:17.200
view reports and summarize that the timing, ah
actually understand how much time they need for

00:23:17.200 --> 00:23:23.600
the fixes to be made. Whereas in many cases the 
fixes are for their own team of content editors

00:23:24.400 --> 00:23:29.040
and decision makers to spend time 
making lots of fixes themselves

00:23:32.400 --> 00:23:39.760
And then also finally looking at the report in 
terms of how crucial it is to making websites more

00:23:39.760 --> 00:23:48.720
accessible, it's only a complement to discussion 
and ongoing discussion with clients to understand

00:23:48.720 --> 00:23:57.040
about how to make the websites more accessible and 
going forward that the report is only a one-off

00:23:57.040 --> 00:24:02.240
snapshot in time. That they need to understand 
that making their website accessible is an ongoing

00:24:02.240 --> 00:24:09.520
process which they need to revisit frequently and 
not just as a one-off to meet this legislation.

00:24:14.640 --> 00:24:20.320
So what's next for our report platform? 
We currently have the platform in our

00:24:20.320 --> 00:24:26.800
own private repository. It's not really in a 
state where we could open source it right now.

00:24:26.800 --> 00:24:32.400
We would like to make it open source as 
potentially a WordPress plugin and also just as

00:24:32.400 --> 00:24:39.840
a static template that you can work as your own 
presentation for any content management system.

00:24:42.080 --> 00:24:49.040
It would also be great to get users to test out 
the platform, not only as content editors, but as

00:24:49.040 --> 00:24:56.240
users viewing the report and we'd like to do 
some usability testing with people to really

00:24:56.240 --> 00:25:03.840
understand what are the problems are in interpreting 
that information and how to make reports more

00:25:03.840 --> 00:25:13.760
accessible. And then finally also to make the whole 
process a lot more streamlined we'd like to link

00:25:13.760 --> 00:25:20.640
those issues into a tracking integration. So for 
example, if you're using a system such as GitHub

00:25:21.600 --> 00:25:27.920
or Trello potentially having a link with it in 
that, so potentially maybe it's something like a

00:25:28.640 --> 00:25:38.880
API so that we could make that whole information 
a lot more open and easier to link to certain

00:25:38.880 --> 00:25:46.400
aspects through the report. And not only developers, 
but anybody else who wants to see the progress of

00:25:46.400 --> 00:25:56.240
changes being fixed and any other information 
basically is a lot more easily accessible.

00:25:56.240 --> 00:26:03.120
So really I'm probably finishing quite 
early for this, but um just as a roundup

00:26:03.120 --> 00:26:08.480
really I just wanted to say thank you to 
everybody who's organized this event .

00:26:08.480 --> 00:26:17.760
And I am happy to take questions now or later.
The company dxw.com, do a whole range of

00:26:18.480 --> 00:26:26.000
work in the public sector. And if you are based 
in London Leeds or anywhere within the UK, uh

00:26:26.000 --> 00:26:33.120
we're happy to talk about how we can work for you 
in making not only the web more accessible but and

00:26:33.920 --> 00:26:38.800
helping public sector services 
and service design. Thank you.

00:26:43.520 --> 00:26:49.120
[Ahmed] Thank you so much Calum, I believe 
we have a lot of time for questions.

00:26:49.840 --> 00:26:56.480
We can, but we certainly are not seeing that 
much questions in the chat so I would like

00:26:56.480 --> 00:27:02.320
